Removing Stopwords¶

In [6]:
def remove_stopwords(text):
    words = text.split()
    filtered_words = [word for word in words if word.lower() not in set(stopwords.words('english'))]
    return ' '.join(filtered_words)

# Load the CSV file for the "Food Court" category
food_court_df = pd.read_csv('C:\\Users\\MOHAMMAD ANZIL\\Desktop\\New folder (14)\\Week3\\Week3-Team3-Novigo-\\Fodd-Week3\\Merged_category_dataset\\Restaurant_tweet.csv')

# Apply the remove_stopwords function to the "Tweet" column
food_court_df['Tweets'] = food_court_df['Tweet'].apply(remove_stopwords)

# Remove the "Tweet" column
food_court_df = food_court_df.drop(columns=['Tweet'])

# Overwrite the original CSV file with the cleaned data
food_court_df.to_csv('Food_Court_tweets.csv', index=False)

Building LDA Model for Positive Tweets¶

In [8]:
# Weightage of the words in the tweets
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df = 0.95, min_df = 2, stop_words =stopwords.words('english'))
x = vectorizer.fit_transform(positive_tweets)
In [9]:
# Lda model
num_topics = 10
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components = num_topics, random_state=40)
lda.fit(x)

In [10]:
num_top_words = 10
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics=[]
In [11]:
# Extracting the topics from LDA model
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[:-num_top_words - 1:-1]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i+1}: {',' .join(topic)}")

Wordcloud for Postive Tweets¶

In [12]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# WordCloud 
res = [' '.join(ele) for ele in topics]
text = ' '.join([word for word in res])
plt.figure(figsize=(20,15), facecolor='None')
wordcloud= WordCloud(max_words=500, width=1600, height=800).generate(text)
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.title('Most frequent words in Positive Tweets (Cafe)', fontsize=19)
plt.show()

Observation for Positive Tweets¶

1. Relaxing Atmosphere:¶

  • Positive tweets mentions cafes as great places to relax, unwind, or enjoy a leisurely break from travel.¶

2. Coffee Quality:¶

  • Many tweets emphasize the good quality of coffee and the availability of unique coffee options like caramel coffee.¶

3. Outdoor Seating:¶

  • Some customers appreciate cafes with outdoor seating, mentioning the appeal of enjoying a coffee while surrounded by fresh air.¶

4. Variety of Snacks:¶

  • Customers highlight the availability of fresh juices, delicious snacks, and a range of coffee options..¶

Observation for Negative Tweets¶

1. Monopoly Complaints:¶

  • Some negative tweets express discontent with cafes at the airport, especially if they have a near-monopoly, as it can lead to complaints about service or menu quality.¶

2. Service Quality:¶

  • Customers express frustration with the slow service, rude staff, or incorrect orders they encountered at cafes.¶

3. Boiled Tea:¶

  • Complaints about the taste and quality of tea, especially if it's served overboiled or lacks customization options.¶

4. Diarrhea Reference:¶

  • Occasionally, customers may associate a cafe with stomach-related issues, indicating dissatisfaction with the food or beverages served.¶
